collection reposition Casanova at the heart of Enlightenment debates on medicine, sociability, gender, and writing. Based on new scholarship, this reappraisal of a key Enlightenment figure explores the period’s fascination with ethnography, its scientific societies, and its understanding of gender, medicine, and women. Casanova is here finally granted his rightful place in cultural and literary history, a place which explains his enduring yet controversial reputation as a figure of seduction and adventure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 18th Century .2bisacsh  aAge of Enlightenment.  aFellini.  aGiacomo Casanova.  aHistory of My Life.  aMedecine.  aautobiography.  aeighteenth-century Europe.  aepistolary writing.  ahistory of Paris.  alibertine.  alove.  aseduction.  asociability.1 aBrin, Raphaëlle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapaci, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelon, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonato, Clorinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIgalens, Jean-Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozul, Mladen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaint-Amand, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStefanovska, Malina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStefanovska, Malina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThomas, Chantal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Christopher B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE